      "type": "short-answer",
      "difficulty": "medium",
      "higherOnly": false,
      "questionText": "Explain why a car travelling at 40 mph has a much longer braking distance than a car travelling at 20 mph.",
      "markScheme": {
        "answer": "At 40 mph, the car has more kinetic energy (KE is proportional to v\u00b2). More work must be done by the brakes to stop the car. Since work = force \u00d7 distance, and the braking force is similar, the distance must be greater. Doubling the speed quadruples the kinetic energy, so braking distance roughly quadruples.",
        "steps": [
          { "mark": 1, "description": "Higher speed means greater kinetic energy" },
          { "mark": 2, "description": "KE is proportional to velocity squared" },
          { "mark": 3, "description": "More work must be done by the brakes to stop the car" },
          { "mark": 4, "description": "Since braking force is roughly constant, greater energy means greater braking distance" }
        ],
        "commonErrors": [
          "Saying braking distance doubles when speed doubles (it quadruples)",
          "Not mentioning the v\u00b2 relationship"
        ]
      },
      "usedAsWorkedExample": false,
      "usedAsYourTurn": false
    },
